{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17474701","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17474701"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T22:23:22+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T22:23:22+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12326"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"12326","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/12326"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.07,0.35,0.47,0.07,0.03]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4846"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"69056"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4846","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4846"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12326"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"54513"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"42"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"2469"},{"type":"tags","id":"4945"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"7824"},{"type":"contributions","id":"8429"},{"type":"contributions","id":"9253"},{"type":"contributions","id":"14776"},{"type":"contributions","id":"14786"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"69056","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/69056"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA three-day-old boy undergoes routine newborn bloodspot screening. He appears well and is feeding normally. He has no significant medical history and his mother had an uncomplicated pregnancy. The screening result shows an immunoreactive trypsinogen level above the 99th percentile.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Repeat immunoreactive trypsinogen measurement","CFTR gene testing","Sweat chloride test","Referral to paediatric respiratory physician","Clinical review in 4-6 weeks"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis case demonstrates the initial positive screening result for cystic fibrosis (CF) in a newborn. Newborn bloodspot screening includes measurement of immunoreactive trypsinogen (IRT), which is typically elevated in CF. However, IRT alone cannot diagnose CF as it has poor specificity.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECFTR gene testing\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate next step as it can rapidly identify disease-causing mutations. Modern genetic testing can screen for over 2000 known CF mutations. Early genetic diagnosis allows for prompt initiation of care and helps predict disease severity based on genotype-phenotype correlations.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERepeat immunoreactive trypsinogen measurement\u003C/strong\u003E is unnecessary as the initial result is already above the threshold for further investigation. IRT levels can be variable and may normalise even in children with CF.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESweat chloride testing\u003C/strong\u003E, while traditionally considered the gold standard for CF diagnosis, can be technically challenging in young infants and may need to be repeated if unsuccessful. With rapid genetic testing now available, it is more efficient to proceed directly to genetic analysis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EReferral to paediatric respiratory physician\u003C/strong\u003E would be appropriate after confirmation of diagnosis but is premature at this stage.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EClinical review in 4-6 weeks\u003C/strong\u003E would cause unnecessary delay in diagnosis. Early identification of CF is crucial as it allows for immediate intervention if needed, particularly in cases with pancreatic insufficiency.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe approach to CF screening varies between regions, but the trend is towards early genetic testing following elevated IRT, as this provides the most rapid and reliable path to diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Newborn screening for cystic fibrosis begins with immunoreactive trypsinogen (IRT) measurement from dried blood spots","A raised IRT requires follow-up genetic testing for CFTR mutations to confirm or exclude cystic fibrosis","Early diagnosis of cystic fibrosis through newborn screening improves clinical outcomes"],"references":["Australian Government Department of Health and Aged Care. \u0027About newborn bloodspot screening\u0027 Online. Australian Government Department of Health and Aged Care website. 2023. Viewed March 2023. Available via: https://www.health.gov.au/our-work/newborn-bloodspot-screening/about-newborn-bloodspot-screening","Cystic Fibrosis Western Australia organisation. \u0027CF Diagnosis\u0027 Cystic Fibrosis Western Australia Website 2023. Viewed March 2023. Available via: https://www.cfwa.org.au/cystic-fibrosis/diagnosis/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"54513"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12326"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"54513","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/54513"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-11T08:56:25+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-11T08:58:52+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4846"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"69056"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"9","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/9"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc76","name":"Paediatrics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"c